===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|talente|lang=ang}}, from plural of {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|talentum||a Grecian weight; a talent of money|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|τάλαντον||balance, a particular weight, especially of gold, sum of money, a talent|tr=talanton|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}. Later senses reinforced by Old French {{term|talent|lang=fro||a talent, also will, inclination, desire}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈtalənt/}}
* {{audio|En-us-talent.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|historical|lang=en}} A [[unit]] of [[weight]] and [[money]] used in [[ancient]] times in Greece, the Roman Empire, and the Middle East. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}
#* '''1611''', Authorized Version, Matthew XXV 14-15:
#*: For the kingdom of heaven is as a man travelling into a far country, who called his own servants, and delivered unto them his goods.  And unto one he gave five '''talents''', to another two, and to another one; to every man according to his several ability; and straightway took his journey.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A [[desire]] or [[inclination]] for something. {{defdate|14th-16th c.}}
#* '''1485''', Sir Thomas Malory, ''Le Morte Darthur'', Book X:
#*: ‘Faythfully,’ seyde Sir Dynadan, ‘I woll nat abyde, for I have suche a '''talente''' to se Sir Trystram that I may nat abyde longe from hym.’
# After Matthew 25, above: A marked natural [[ability]] or [[skill]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: ''He has the '''talent''' of touching his nose with his tongue.''
# {{context|business|media|sports|lang=en}} People of talent, viewed collectively; a talented person. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}
#: The director searched their '''talent''' pool to fill the new opening.
# {{context|slang|lang=en}} The men or (especially) women of a place or area, judged by their [[attractiveness]]. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}
#: ''Not much '''talent''' in this bar tonight – let's hit the clubs.''
#* '''2011''', Nic Venter, ''Wow! What a Life!'' (page 179)
#*: I went down to the beach front, of course, for that was the first thing that all Vaalies did: to look at the sea and to check the '''talent''' on the beach.

